{"id":"1806.01189","submitter":"Alok Pan","authors":"Asmita Kumari and A. K. Pan","title":"Faithful Pointer for qubit measurement","comments":null,"journal-ref":"International Journal of Theoretical Physics, 57, 554 (2018)","doi":"10.1007/s10773-017-3588-z","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In the context of von Neumann projective measurement scenario for a qubit\nsystem, it is widely believed that the mutual orthogonality between the\npost-interaction pointer states is the sufficient condition for achieving the\nideal measurement situation. However, for experimentally verifying the\nobservable probabilities, the real space distinction between the pointer\ndistributions corresponding to post-interaction pointer states play crucial\nrole. It is implicitly assumed that mutual orthogonality ensures the support\nbetween the post-interaction pointer distributions to be disjoint. We point out\nthat mutual orthogonality (formal idealness) does \\emph{not} necessarily imply\nthe real space distinguishability (operational idealness), but converse is\ntrue. In fact, for the commonly referred Gaussian wavefunction, it is possible\nto obtain a measurement situation which is formally ideal but fully nonideal\noperationally. In this paper, we derive a class of pointer states, that we call\nfaithful pointers, for which the degree of formal (non)idealness is equal to\nthe operational (non)idealness. In other words, for the faithful pointers, if a\nmeasurement situation is formally ideal then it is operationally ideal and vice\nversa.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 4 Jun 2018 16:34:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-06-05"}
